California Daycare Fraud Investigation Dashboard

1159 flagged facilities analyzed for fraud indicators

Risk Scoring Methodology & Fraud Indicators

â–¼

This analysis uses patterns identified in the Minnesota "Feeding Our Future" fraud case ($250M stolen) and the San Diego UMI Learning Center case ($3.7M stolen) to flag potentially fraudulent California daycare facilities.

Risk Score Calculation (0-10 scale)

Factor Points Why This Matters
COVID-Era License
Licensed in 2020, 2021, or 2022		 +2 During COVID, emergency childcare funding increased dramatically with reduced oversight. Fraudsters exploited the system by opening fake facilities to collect subsidies. The Minnesota fraud ring operated primarily during 2020-2022.
Closed/Inactive Status
Facility is no longer operating		 +2 Fraudulent facilities often close quickly after collecting payments, before investigations begin. A closed facility that operated briefly during COVID is highly suspicious.
Short Operation Period
Open less than 24 months before closing		 +3 Legitimate daycares typically operate for many years. "Pop-up" facilities that open, collect subsidies, and close within 1-2 years match the fraud pattern. This is the highest-weighted factor because it's the clearest fraud signal.
Shared Phone Number
Same phone as another facility		 +2 Multiple "separate" facilities sharing phone numbers suggests they're actually controlled by the same person/organization. This was a key pattern in the NOORI family network identified in El Cajon (22 facilities, 14 phone numbers).
Generic Business Name
Names like "ABC Learning" or "Little Stars"		 +1 While many legitimate daycares have generic names, fraudsters often use unremarkable names that don't draw attention. Lower weight because this alone isn't suspicious.

Additional Red Flags (Not in Score)

"No Children Present" During Inspection
When state inspectors visit a licensed daycare and find no children present, it raises serious questions. A facility billing the state for childcare should have children. This finding comes from actual CCLD inspection reports scraped from the California transparency database.

Found in 22 of 104 high-risk facilities checked (21%)
License Cycling
When a licensee repeatedly closes facilities and immediately reopens with new license numbers, it may indicate attempts to reset inspection history or avoid scrutiny. The NOORI family network shows this pattern clearly: closing one license and opening a new one on the same day.
Geographic Clustering
Unusual concentrations of new facilities in specific ZIP codes may indicate organized fraud. El Cajon (92020, 92021) and Santa Maria (93454, 93458) showed the highest COVID-era license concentrations.

Risk Score Interpretation

Score Risk Level Interpretation
9-10 Critical Multiple major red flags. Highest priority for investigation. Likely matches fraud patterns.
7-8 Very High Several concerning factors present. Should be investigated.
5-6 Elevated Some risk factors present. May warrant review if resources allow.
0-4 Lower Fewer red flags, but presence on this list means at least one risk factor exists.

Data Sources

  • Facility Data: California Community Care Licensing Division (CCLD) - 39,184 total facilities
  • Inspection Reports: CCLD Transparency API - scraped for risk 9+ facilities
  • Analysis Date: January 2026

Limitations

  • Cannot verify which facilities actually receive CACFP (federal food program) funds
  • Cannot access state subsidy payment records without Public Records Act request
  • Family childcare home addresses marked "UNAVAILABLE" for privacy
  • Some legitimate facilities may score high due to COVID-era timing or normal business closures
